Accessibility Issues Outside the Development Phase

01
On this page
  1. Inaccessible Brand Colors
  2. Mobile Accessibility Issues
  3. Icon Buttons without Text Labels
  4. Embedded Content with Accessibility Problems
  5. Inaccessible Overlay Solutions

We want to ensure that we're not forgetting that user experience is a big part of making good digital experiences, and accessibility is a massive part of that. We need to center accessibility and people with disabilities earlier in the software development life cycle.

Access can't always be teased out of development.

When you are faced with accessibility issues that can't be fixed with code, the job of creating a good digital experience is far from done. You don’t want to be limited by what you can accomplish with code alone.

In this lesson, we’ll talk about common “non-code” accessibility situations and approaches for solving them.

Inaccessible Brand Colors

A very common scenario is brand colors that don't meet contrast requirements.

Sufficient contrast between foreground and background colors helps to ensure that more people will be able to read and use our web applications.

Suppose you're running some accessibility tests and find that your site’s colors don't meet contrast requirements. What do you do? Depending on the organization you work in, you might not be able to fix it. It might be an accessibility issue that isn’t easily resolved.

The way that we would need to fix it is to have conversations with brand designers and other stakeholders and make it clear that a change needs to be made.

Maybe your organization needs an alternate set of colors, or maybe designers can set rules about when certain colors can’t be combined.

You've got options, but it requires a deeper conversation.

Mobile Accessibility Issues

Accessible mobile interfaces that require swiping can't always be fixed in development.

Suppose the interface doesn't allow a screen reader user to complete actions on your web app’s mobile interface. This might mean that you are required to go back to the design team and determine how the interface could be adjusted.

For example, adding labeled buttons to do the same actions as left or right swiping would be accessible while a mobile screen reader is running. But they would have to be designed into the interface, which would be a significant change.

We can't fix everything with code and mobile interfaces also need to be taken into account.

Icon Buttons without Text Labels

A common design trend is to use minimalist buttons that only consist of an icon with no accompanying text.

They might look sleek and not take up much room on the screen (especially on mobile), but it may not always be clear to your audience what the buttons actually do!

To make things more frustrating, the icon button can become hard to see if it is over an image or video.

Icon buttons need to ensure that their function can be clear and discoverable. If you were given a design to develop without icon labels, it would require collaboration with your design team to talk through the available options. Testing with users would be a good start to make sure the icons are intuitive and usable. Making text labeling configurable would be another great option.

It can be difficult sometimes to rock the boat at an organization when stakeholders have already signed off on a design. By tying the concern back to user experience and aiming to validate the usability of designs with actual users, hopefully, improvements can be made that benefits everyone.

Embedded Content with Accessibility Problems

You might find yourself in a scenario where the marketing team wants you to embed content from another source that they strongly feel will add customer value.

The problem with third-party content using iframes is that they can bring their own accessibility issues into your application. Your organization is still on the hook for the accessibility of third-party content even if you don’t control the code from its source.

In this scenario, you will likely need to have a conversation with the marketing or product leadership teams about pitting potential added value vs. access and compliance.

You can try to go to the vendor and report accessibility issues with the hope that they fix them. In some cases, they'll be enthusiastic about making improvements, and some may even jump at the chance to make improvements. But unfortunately, the reality is that many third-party vendors don't have the knowledge, care, or time to do so.

Inaccessible Overlay Solutions

Some sites offer an overlay widget for their site in an attempt to provide a more accessible experience with limited investment.

This decision is often made based on not wanting to spend the cycles to design and develop something with accessibility in mind from the start.

Choosing to use an overlay is a huge missed opportunity.

Teams building the product will continue the inaccessible cycle by never getting the chance to learn how to make something more accessible.

Worse, these overlays often don’t fix accessibility problems, and using them doesn’t hold up in a court of law.

As someone passionate about designing and developing inclusive sites from the beginning, the add-on culture goes against that philosophy. Bolting on a quick fix for the long term rather than architecting something accessible from within is a real shame, especially since feedback from people with disabilities has been that the quick fixes don’t work. There are multiple layers to the problem here.

If you find yourself working in an environment where an accessibility overlay is proposed, call it what it is: a way to cut corners that should be avoided at all costs. This is a hill I personally would be “willing to die on” as I talked with stakeholders, as it would actively work against the efforts to design and develop accessible sites from the ground up.
